The personal name was popular throughout Christian Europe in the Middle Ages, having been bestowed by Christ as a byname on the apostle Simon bar Jonah, the brother of Andrew. The name was chosen by Christ for its symbolic significance (John 1:42, Matt. 16:18); Saint Peter is regarded as the founding head of the Christian Church in view of Christ's saying, ‘Thou art Peter and upon this rock I will build my Church’. In Christian Germany in the early Middle Ages this was the most frequent personal name of non-ancient Germanic origin until the 14th century. In North America, this surname has also absorbed cognates from other languages, for example Czech   Petr  , Polish <b>Piotr</b> and <b>Pietr</b>, Albanian <b>Pjetri</b> (from the personal name <i>Pjetër</i>, definite form <i>Pjetri</i>), and also their derivatives (see examples at   Peterson  ). It has also been adopted as a surname by Ashkenazic Jews."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Guimarães","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Eduardo, Fernando, Luiz, Roberto, Jorge, Marcos, Mario, Viriato, Abilio, Albino.  Portuguese Joaquim, Paulo, Amadeu, Anabela, Joao, Marcio, Vasco.","Portuguese (<b>Guimarães</b>): habitational name from any ofvarious places called Guimarães, especially the provincial capitalof Minho; its name is derived from an ancient Germanic personal name."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Fernão","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: habitational name from any of various places called Fernau, Fernow, or Viernau."],"variants":[{"name":"Fearnow","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Fernau   or of <b>Virnau</b> (also <b>Viernow</b>), a habitational name from Viernau in Thuringia."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1356752,"age":12,"year":"1112","julianDay":2127209,"description":"Afonso inherits the County of Portugal, a province of Castile.","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"When Fernão Peres de Guimarães was born about 1100, in Portugal, his father, Pero Fromarigues de Guimarães, was 175 and his mother, D.ª Gotinha Fromariz, was -90. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Usco Godins de Lanhoso. He died about 1178, in Pombeiro de Riba Vizela, Felgueiras, Porto, Portugal, at the age of 80."},"et":{"aproximadamente 1100–aproximadamente 1178":"umbes 1100–umbes 1178","1100–1178":"1100–1178","1105–Male":"1105–Surnud","1111–Male":"1111–Surnud","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","1160–1208":"1160–1208","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","0926–Male":"0926–Surnud","1192–Female":"1192–Surnud","aproximadamente 1100":"umbes 1100","aproximadamente 1160":"umbes 1160","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","aproximadamente 1178":"umbes 1178","1192":"1192","um 1160":"umbes 1160","1105":"1105","1112":"1112","1178":"1178","1111":"1111","1100":"1100","0926":"0926","1208":"1208","Pombeiro de Riba Vizela, Felgueiras, Porto, Portugal":"Pombeiro de Riba Vizela, Felgueiras, Porto, Portugal","Riba de Vizela, Braga, Portugal":"Braga, Portugal","Portugal":"Portugal"},"fi":{"aproximadamente 1100–aproximadamente 1178":"noin 1100–noin 1178","1100–1178":"1100–1178","1105–Male":"1105–Kuollut","1111–Male":"1111–Kuollut","1140–Female":"1140–Kuollut","1160–1208":